ublican}}|41.0% ''206''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''55.7%''' ''280''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|3.4% ''17''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1920|1920]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''50.3%''' ''253''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|49.5% ''249''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.2% ''1''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1916|1916]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|49.0% ''217''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''50.3%''' ''223''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|0.7% ''3''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 1912|1912]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|11.8% ''48''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''62.9%''' ''256''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|25.3% ''103''\n|}\n{{Hidden end}}\n\n==Festivals==\nThe King George Fall Festival is held the second weekend of October in King George. All proceeds from this event go to support the Volunteer King George Fire & Rescue.\n\nThe Fall Festival also includes a parade through town, a carnival, a craft fair, a car show, a dance, a 5-K run, and the Fall Festival Queens Pageant. The King George Fall Festival began in October 1959.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kgfallfestival.com/ |title=King George Fall Festival |publisher=King George Fall Festival |accessdate=December 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Communities==\n===Census-designated places===\n* [[Dahlgren, Virginia|Dahlgren]]\n* [[Dahlgren Center, Virginia|Dahlgren Center]]\n* [[Fairview Beach, Virginia|Fairview Beach]]\n* [[King George, Virginia|King George]]\n* [[Passapatanzy, Virginia|Passapatanzy]]\n\n===Other unincorporated communities===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Arnolds Corner, Virginia|Arnolds Corner]]\n* [[Berthaville, Virginia|Berthaville]]\n* [[Dogue, Virginia|Dogue]]\n* [[Hampstead, King George County, Virginia|Hampstead]]\n* [[Jersey, Virginia|Jersey]]\n* [[Ninde, Virginia|Ninde]]\n* [[Owens, Virginia|Owens]]\n* [[Port Conway, Virginia|Port Conway]]\n* [[Rollins Fork, Virginia|Rollins Fork]]\n* [[Sealston, Virginia|Sealston]]\n* [[Shiloh, King George County, Virginia|Shiloh]]\n* [[Weedonville, Virginia|Weedonville]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Notable residents==\n* [[James Madison]], fourth President of the United States\n* [[Mark Warner]], US Senator, maintains a residence and farm\n* [[Krystal Ball]], political talk show co-host and one-time Congressional candidate, grew up in King George\n* [[Collette Wolfe]], actress, grew up in King George, Virginia<ref>{{cite web|title=Colette Wolfe|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm2180792/|publisher=IMDB}}</ref>\n* [[Jermon Bushrod]], guard for the New Orleans Saints in the National Football League (NFL), grew up in King George, Virginia<ref>[[Jermon Bushrod]]</ref>\n* [[Al Bumbry]], Major League Baseball Player\n* [[Nell Zink]], American novelist, grew up in King George County<ref>{{cite journal |last=Schulz |first=Kathryn |date=May 18, 2015 |title=Outside In |url=http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/05/18/outside-in |journal=New Yorker}}</ref>\n* [[Dorthia Cottrell]], Musician, grew up in King George County\n\n==See also==\n* [[Caledon State Park]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in King George County, Virginia]]\n* [[Northern Neck George Washington Birthplace AVA]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|King George County, Virginia}}\n* [https://www.kinggeorgecountyva.gov King George County Administration]\n* [http://www.kgcs.k12.va.us/ King George County Public Schools]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20181030035435/http://www.kghistory.org/ King George County Historical Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120306181817/http://resources.rootsweb.ancestry.com/USA/VA/KingGeorge/ RootsWeb King George County]\n* [http://www.onlinegis.net/VaKingGeorge/ King George County Online GIS]\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = King George County, Virginia\n|North     = [[Charles County, Maryland]]\n|Northeast =\n|East      = [[Westmoreland County, Virginia|Westmoreland County]]\n|Southeast = [[Essex County, Virginia|Essex County]]\n|South     =\n|Southwest = [[Caroline County, Virginia|Caroline County]]\n|West      = [[Stafford County, Virginia|Stafford County]]\n|Northwest =\n}}\n\n{{King George County, Virginia}}\n{{Virginia}}\n\n{{Coord|38.26|-77.15|display=title|type:adm2nd_region:US-VA_source:UScensus1990}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:King George County, Virginia| ]]\n[[Category:Virginia counties]]\n[[Category:Virginia counties on the Potomac River]]\n[[Category:Northern Neck]]\n[[Category:1720 establishments in Virginia]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1720]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Prince George County, Virginia}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county|\n county = King George County|\n state = Virginia |\n seal = King George Seal.jpg |\n founded = 1720|\n seat wl= King George |\n largest city wl = King George|\n city type = CDP|\n area_total_sq_mi =188 |\n area_land_sq_mi =180 |\n area_water_sq_mi =21 |\n area percentage = 4.3 |\n population_as_of = 2010 |\n population_total = 23584 |\n pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/> |\n pop_est_as_of = 2018 |\n population_est = 26575 |\n population_density_km2 = auto |\n web = www.kinggeorgecountyva.gov|\n ex image = King George VA courthouse.JPG|\n ex image cap = King George County Courthouse|\n ex image size = 225px\n| time zone = Eastern\n| district = 1st\n| named for = [[George I of Great Britain|George I]]\n}}\n\n'''King George County''' is a [[county (United States)|county]] located in the [[Commonwealth of Virginia]]. As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], the population was 23,584.<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/51/51099.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=January 3, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607061927/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/51/51099.html|archivedate=June 7, 2011}}</ref> Its [[county seat]] is [[King George, Virginia|King George]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web|url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |accessdate=2011-06-07 |title=Find a County |publisher=National Association of Counties |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110531210815/http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx |archivedate=2011-05-31 }}</ref>\n\nThe county's largest employer is the U.S. [[Naval Surface Warfare Center Dahlgren Division]]. It is adjacent to the two-lane, 2-mile long [[Harry W. Nice Memorial Bridge]] carrying [[U.S. Route 301 in Virginia|U.S. Highway 301]] over the [[Potomac River]].\nIt contains the ZIP codes 22448 ([[Dahlgren, Virginia|Dahlgren]]) and 22485 (all other areas within King George).  It is within the area code 540 and contains the exchanges: 775, 644, 663, and 653.\n\n==History==\n[[Indigenous peoples]] of varying cultures lived along the waterways for thousands of years before Europeans arrived.  Among the historic [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]] tribes who came into conflict with the [[England|English]] were the [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]]-speaking [[Nanzatico]]. In 1704 colonists retaliated for the tribe's attacking the farm of John Rowley, \"known for his disputes\" with them.  They captured and shipped 40 people, including children older than 12, to [[Antigua]] in the [[Caribbean]], where they were sold into [[slavery]].<ref>[http://www.appomattoxhistory.com/2010/eleven-new-state-historical-highway-markers-approved.html \"Eleven New State Historical Highway Markers Approved\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707153454/http://www.appomattoxhistory.com/2010/eleven-new-state-historical-highway-markers-approved.html |date=2011-07-07 }}, Appomattox County History, 23 January 2010, accessed 19 April 2010</ref>\n\nKing George County was established in 1720 when land was split from [[Richmond County, Virginia]]. The county is named for [[George I of Great Britain|King George I]] of [[Kingdom of Great Britain|Great Britain]].<ref>{{cite book | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ | title=The Origin of Certain Place Names in the United States | publisher=Govt. Print. Off. | author=Gannett, Henry | year=1905 | pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_9V1IAAAAMAAJ/page/n174 175]}}</ref> It was substantially reorganized in 1776 and 1777, with land swapped with both Stafford and Westmoreland Counties to form the modern boundaries.\n\nOn March 16, 1751, [[James Madison]], the fourth [[President of the United States]], was born in [[Port Conway, Virginia|Port Conway]] in southern King George County at [[Belle Grove (Port Conway, Virginia)|Belle Grove]] plantation, the childhood home of his mother, Eleanor Rose \"Nellie\" Conway, the daughter of its owner, Francis Conway, for whom Port Conway was named. Two-time Governor of Virginia, [[William \"Extra Billy\" Smith]], was born at Marengo in 1797.\n\nOn May 1, 1861 during the [[American Civil War]], [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]] installed [[artillery]] at Mathias Point in order to blockade the [[Potomac River]]. On June 27, the steamer ''Thomas Freeborn'' bombarded Mathias Point in an attempt to drive away the soldiers who were manning the weapons. Confederate soldiers fired back from Mathias Point, striking and mortally wounding Commander [[James H. Ward]] of the Freeborn, who became the first [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] [[naval]] officer to die in the Civil War.\n[[Image:King George County landscape.jpg|thumb|left|Landscape in King George County]]\n\nWhile trying to elude [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] [[cavalry]], [[John Wilkes Booth]] and [[David Herold]] crossed into the county from [[Maryland]] on April 21, 1865 after assassinating US president [[Abraham Lincoln]]. Booth and Herold landed at the mouth of Gambo Creek, before meeting with [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] agents, who guided their passage to [[Port Conway, Virginia|Port Conway]], where they would cross into [[Port Royal, Virginia|Port Royal]], in [[Caroline County, Virginia]]. King George County has one of the first railroad enabled landfills and it was developed by a Blake Van Leer. Van Leer is also a member of the historical [[Van Leer (surname)| Van Leer family]]<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.kinggeorgecountyva.gov/ArchiveCenter/ViewFile/Item/1003| title= King George County Archive) | accessdate= September 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau|U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|188|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|180|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|8|sqmi}} (4.3%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020527061848/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|archive-date=2002-05-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nKing George County is located on the [[Northern Neck]] and is bounded on the north by the Potomac River, which lies in [[Charles County, Maryland]]. It is bounded on the south by the [[Rappahannock River]] across which lie [[Caroline County, Virginia|Caroline]] and [[Essex County, Virginia|Essex]] Counties; on the east by [[Westmoreland County, Virginia|Westmoreland County]] and on the west by [[Stafford County, Virginia|Stafford County]].\n\n===National protected area===\n* [[Rappahannock River Valley National Wildlife Refuge]] (part) Bishop, Styer, and Toby's Point units\n\n===Major Highways===\n* {{Jct|state=VA|US|301}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|3}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|205}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|206}}\n* {{Jct|state=VA|SR|218}}\n\n==Demographics==\n{{US Census population\n|1790= 7366\n|1800= 6749\n|1810= 6454\n|1820= 6116\n|1830= 6397\n|1840= 5927\n|1850= 5971\n|1860= 6571\n|1870= 5742\n|1880= 6397\n|1890= 6641\n|1900= 6918\n|1910= 6378\n|1920= 5762\n|1930= 5297\n|1940= 5431\n|1950= 6710\n|1960= 7243\n|1970= 8039\n|1980= 10543\n|1990= 13527\n|2000= 16803\n|2010= 23584\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=26575\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=July 14, 2019}}</ref>\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref name=\"DecennialCensus\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=Census of Population and Housing|publisher=Census.gov|accessdate=June 4, 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\nAs of the [[census]]<ref name=\"GR8\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder.census.gov|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212221153/http://factfinder.census.gov/main.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=2020-02-12|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-05-14|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> of 2010, there were 23,584 people, 9,411 households, and 4,525 families residing in the county. The [[population density]] was 93 people per square mile (36/km\u00b2). There were 6,820 housing units at an average density of 38 per square&nbsp;mile (15/km\u00b2). The racial makeup of the county was 76.7% [[Race (United States Census)|White]], 17.9% [[Race (United States Census)|Black]] or [[Race (United States Census)|African American]], 0.5% [[Race (United States Census)|Native American]], 1.2% [[Race (United States Census)|Asian]], 0.1% [[Race (United States Census)|Pacific Islander]], 0.8% from [[Race (United States Census)|other races]], and 2.9% from two or more races. 3.3% of the population were [[Race (United States Census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (United States Census)|Latino]] of any race.\n\nThere were 6,091 households out of which 38.00% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 59.50% were [[Marriage|married couples]] living together, 10.50% had a female householder with no husband present, and 25.70% were non-families. 20.40% of all households were made up of individuals and 6.00% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 2.70 and the average family size was 3.12.\n\nIn the county, the population was spread out with 27.80% under the age of 18, 8.20% from 18 to 24, 31.70% from 25 to 44, 22.70% from 45 to 64, and 9.60% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 35 years. For every 100 females, there were 101.00 males. For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 99.40 males.\n\nThe median income for a household in the county was $49,882, and the median income for a family was $55,160. Males had a median income of $38,600 versus $26,350 for females. The [[per capita income]] for the county was $21,562. About 4.40% of families and 5.60% of the population were below the [[poverty line]], including 6.10% of those under age 18 and 6.40% of those age 65 or over.\n\n==Government==\n===Board of Supervisors===\n* County Administrator: Neiman C. Young, PhD\n* Member/Vice-Chair (At Large): Ann C Cupka\n* Member/Chairperson (Shiloh): Cathy Binder\n* Member (Madison): Richard Granger \n* Member (Monroe): Jeffery L. Bueche\n* Member (Dahlgren): Jeff Stonehill\n\n===Constitutional officers===\n* Clerk of the Circuit Court: Charles V. \"Vic\" Mason (I)\n* Commissioner of the Revenue: Jo Ann Hall Ando (I)\n* Commonwealth's Attorney: Keri A. Gusmann (I)\n* Sheriff: Christopher A Giles(I)\n* Treasurer: Alice L. Moore (I)\n\nKing George is represented by Republicans Ryan T. McDougle and Richard H. Stuart in the Virginia Senate, Republican Margaret Bevans Ransone in the Virginia House of Delegates, and Republican Robert J. \"Rob\" Wittman in the U.S. House of Representatives.\n\n{{Hidden begin\n|titlestyle = background:#ccccff;\n|title      = Presidential elections results\n}}\n{| align=\"center\" border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"float:right; margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|+ '''Presidential elections results'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|last=Leip|first=David|website=uselectionatlas.org|access-date=2018-08-20}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=lightgrey\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n! [[Third Party (United States)|Third parties]]\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2016|2016]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''60.9%''' ''7,341''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|33.3% ''4,007''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|5.8% ''702''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2012|2012]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''58.3%''' ''6,604''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|39.5% ''4,477''\n|  style=\"text-align:center; background:honeyDew;\"|2.2% ''244''\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''[[United States presidential election in Virginia, 2008|2008]]'''\n|  style=\"text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|'''56.2%''' ''5,888''\n|  st