ontrol}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pascal, Blaise}}\n[[Category:1623 births]]\n[[Category:1662 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Clermont-Ferrand]]\n[[Category:French Roman Catholic writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Auvergne-Rh\u00f4ne-Alpes]]\n[[Category:17th-century French writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:17th-century philosophers]]\n[[Category:Aphorists]]\n[[Category:Blaise Pascal| ]]\n[[Category:Christian apologists]]\n[[Category:Christian humanists]]\n[[Category:Roman Catholic mystics]]\n[[Category:Critics of atheism]]\n[[Category:Converts to Roman Catholicism]]\n[[Category:Fluid dynamicists]]\n[[Category:French mathematicians]]\n[[Category:French philosophers]]\n[[Category:French physicists]]\n[[Category:17th-century French theologians]]\n[[Category:17th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Hypochondriacs]]\n[[Category:Jansenists]]\n[[Category:Probability theorists]]\n[[Category:Catholic philosophers]]\n[[Category:17th-century Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Burials at Saint-\u00c9tienne-du-Mont]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eThe Provincial Letters:title formatting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Blaise_Pascal"}
{"title_page": "Elizabeth Berridge, Baroness Berridge", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Berridge\n|image            = Baroness Berridge.jpg\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       = \n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Department for Education|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the School System]]\n|primeminister    = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start       = 13 February 2020\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Theodore Agnew, Baron Agnew of Oulton|The Lord Agnew of Oulton]]\n|successor        = \n|office3          = [[Baroness-in-Waiting]]<br>[[Government Whip]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start3      = 30 July 2019\n|term_end3        = \n|predecessor3     = [[Deborah Stedman-Scott, Baroness Stedman-Scott|The Baroness Stedman-Scott]]\n|successor3       = \n|office5          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5      = 18 January 2011<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_name        = Elizabeth Rose Berridge\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|3|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place      = [[Rutland]], [[England]]\n|residence        = \n|death_date       =\n|death_place      =\n|restingplace     = \n|nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|occupation       = Member of the [[House of Lords]]\n|spouse           = \n|education        = [[Bachelor of Arts#United Kingdom and Ireland|BA]] (Hons) Law\n|alma_mater       = [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Rose Berridge, Baroness Berridge''' (born 22 March 1972) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[politician]] and member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37710.stm|title=Baroness Berridge|publisher=BBC Democracy|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBorn and educated in the county of [[Rutland]], Lady Berridge attended [[Vale of Catmose College]] and [[Rutland College]] in [[Oakham]]. She then studied Law at [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]], and undertook barrister's training at the [[Inns of Court School of Law]] in London. Her professional career was as a barrister before she was appointed Executive Director of the [[Conservative Christian Fellowship]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccfwebsite.com/lifepeerageawarded.shtml |title=Life Peerage Awarded to CCF Director |accessdate=3 February 2011 |publisher=[[Conservative Christian Fellowship|Conservative Christian Fellowship Ltd]] |date=19 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306154047/http://www.ccfwebsite.com/lifepeerageawarded.shtml |archive-date=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShe fought [[Stockport (UK Parliament constituency)|Stockport]] for the Conservatives in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nBaroness Berridge is also part of the Advisory Council of the [[Foundation for Relief and Reconciliation in the Middle East]] which supports the  work of [[Canon Andrew White]], the \"vicar of Baghdad\".\n\nShe is a founding and steering committee member of the [[International Panel of Parliamentarians for Freedom of Religion or Belief]].\n\n==House of Lords==\nOn 18 January 2011, Berridge was created a [[life peer]]ess as '''Baroness Berridge''', ''of [[Vale of Catmose|The Vale of Catmose]] in the [[County of Rutland]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59677 |date=21 January 2011 |page=965}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 20 January 2011.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/minutes/110121/ldordpap.htm#minproc House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings for Thursday 20 January 2011].</ref> where she sits on the Conservative benches. Born in 1972, she was the second youngest female member of the House of Lords, after [[Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho|Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/faqs/house-of-lords-faqs/lords-members/ |title=FAQs: Membership and principal office holders |publisher=House of Lords Information Office |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe is Chair of the All Party Group on International Religious Freedom.\n\nShe is Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the School System at the Department for Education and Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Minister for Women) at the Department for International Trade<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/ministers/minister-for-women</ref>.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn 5 October 2017, Baroness Berridge was awarded the 2017 International Religious Liberty Award by the [[International Center for Law and Religion Studies]] and [[J. Reuben Clark Law Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iclrs.org/index.php?pageId=1&contentId=1&blurbId=86128|title=Baroness Elizabeth Berridge Receives 2017 International Religious Liberty Award|website=International Center for Law and Religion Studies|access-date=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baronessberridge.com Personal website]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/baroness_berridge Baroness Berridge, TheyWorkForYou]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berridge, Elizabeth Berridge, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:People from Rutland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Emmanuel College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Catmose College]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name             = The Baroness Berridge\n|image            = Baroness Berridge.jpg\n|imagesize        = \n|smallimage       = \n|caption          = \n|office           = [[Department for Education|Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the School System]]\n|primeminister    = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start       = 13 February 2020\n|term_end         = \n|predecessor      = [[Theodore Agnew, Baron Agnew of Oulton|The Lord Agnew of Oulton]]\n|successor        = \n|office3          = [[Baroness-in-Waiting]]<br>[[Government Whip]]\n|primeminister3   = [[Boris Johnson]]\n|term_start3      = 30 July 2019\n|term_end3        = \n|predecessor3     = [[Deborah Stedman-Scott, Baroness Stedman-Scott|The Baroness Stedman-Scott]]\n|successor3       = \n|office5          = [[Member of the House of Lords]]<br/>[[Lords Temporal|Lord Temporal]]\n|term_start5      = 18 January 2011<br/>[[Life Peerage]]\n|birth_name        = Elizabeth Rose Berridge\n|birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1972|3|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place      = [[Rutland]], [[England]]\n|residence        = \n|death_date       =\n|death_place      =\n|restingplace     = \n|nationality      = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n|party            = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n|occupation       = Member of the [[House of Lords]]\n|spouse           = \n|education        = [[Bachelor of Arts#United Kingdom and Ireland|BA]] (Hons) Law\n|alma_mater       = [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]]\n}}\n'''Elizabeth Rose Berridge, Baroness Berridge''' (born 22 March 1972) is a British [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[politician]] and member of the [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/democracylive/hi/representatives/profiles/37710.stm|title=Baroness Berridge|publisher=BBC Democracy|accessdate=22 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBorn and educated in the county of [[Rutland]], Lady Berridge attended [[Vale of Catmose College]] and [[Rutland College]] in [[Oakham]]. She then studied Law at [[Emmanuel College, Cambridge]], and undertook barrister\u2019s training at the [[Inns of Court School of Law]] in London. Her professional career was as a barrister before she was appointed Executive Director of the [[Conservative Christian Fellowship]] in 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccfwebsite.com/lifepeerageawarded.shtml |title=Life Peerage Awarded to CCF Director |accessdate=3 February 2011 |publisher=[[Conservative Christian Fellowship|Conservative Christian Fellowship Ltd]] |date=19 November 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306154047/http://www.ccfwebsite.com/lifepeerageawarded.shtml |archive-date=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nShe fought [[Stockport (UK Parliament constituency)|Stockport]] for the Conservatives in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]].\n\nBaroness Berridge is also part of the Advisory Council of the [[Foundation for Relief and Reconciliation in the Middle East]] which supports the  work of [[Canon Andrew White]], the \"vicar of Baghdad\".\n\nShe is a founding and steering committee member of the [[International Panel of Parliamentarians for Freedom of Religion or Belief]].\n\n==House of Lords==\nOn 18 January 2011, Berridge was created a [[life peer]]ess as '''Baroness Berridge''', ''of [[Vale of Catmose|The Vale of Catmose]] in the [[County of Rutland]]'',<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59677 |date=21 January 2011 |page=965}}</ref> and was [[Introduction (House of Lords)|introduced]] in the [[House of Lords]] on 20 January 2011.<ref>[https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/ld201011/minutes/110121/ldordpap.htm#minproc House of Lords Minutes of Proceedings for Thursday 20 January 2011].</ref> where she sits on the Conservative benches. Born in 1972, she was the second youngest female member of the House of Lords, after [[Martha Lane Fox, Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho|Baroness Lane-Fox of Soho]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.uk/about/faqs/house-of-lords-faqs/lords-members/ |title=FAQs: Membership and principal office holders |publisher=House of Lords Information Office |accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe is Chair of the All Party Group on International Religious Freedom.\n\nShe is Parliamentary Under Secretary of State for the School System at the Department for Education and Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Minister for Women) at the Department for International Trade<ref>https://www.gov.uk/government/ministers/minister-for-women</ref>.\n\n== Awards ==\nOn 5 October 2017, Baroness Berridge was awarded the 2017 International Religious Liberty Award by the [[International Center for Law and Religion Studies]] and [[J. Reuben Clark Law Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iclrs.org/index.php?pageId=1&contentId=1&blurbId=86128|title=Baroness Elizabeth Berridge Receives 2017 International Religious Liberty Award|website=International Center for Law and Religion Studies|access-date=5 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.baronessberridge.com Personal website]\n*[https://www.theyworkforyou.com/peer/baroness_berridge Baroness Berridge, TheyWorkForYou]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Berridge, Elizabeth Berridge, Baroness}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Female life peers]]\n[[Category:People from Rutland]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Emmanuel College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People educated at Catmose College]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elizabeth_Berridge,_Baroness_Berridge"}
